---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_HEADER_TITLE } from '../consts';
const astroUrl = "https://astro.build/";
const gitHubUrl = "https://github.com/ibbrett";
const gitHubProfileImage = "https://github.com/ibbrett.png";
const ecma262Url = "https://www.ecma-international.org/wp-content/uploads/ECMA-262_1st_edition_june_1997.pdf";
const refUrl = "https://github.com/ibbrett/astro-transition-typescript/tree/master/README/README-REFERENCES.md";
const featuresUrl = "/astro-transition-typescript/blog";
const aboutUrl = "/astro-transition-typescript/about";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} header_title={SITE_HEADER_TITLE} />
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header title={SITE_TITLE} />
		<main class="slide-right">
			<div class="home-header">
			<a href={gitHubUrl} target="_blank"><img src={gitHubProfileImage}></a> 
			<h4 class="label">Hello ECMAScript Engineers!</h4>
		</div>
			<p>
				This site is a simple <a href={astroUrl} target="_blank">Astro</a> blog with view transitions showcasing the different versions of 
				ECMAScript.
			</p>
			<p>
				JavaScript was created in 1995 by Brendan Eich of Netscape.
			</p>
			<p>
				To standardize the language Netscape submitted JavaScript to the European Computer Manufacturers Association in 1996.
				This led to the first official release of <a href={ecma262Url} target="_blank">ECMA-262</a> in 1997.
			</p>
			<p>
				As a full stack engineer who uses both Node on the backend and React on the frontend with JavaScript/TypeScript these updates are wonderful, adding more and more options to write increasingly better code. 
			</p>
			<p>To find out more about: </p>
			<ul>
				<li>ECMAScript versions, take a look at the <code><a href={featuresUrl}>Blog</a></code></li>
				<li>me, take a look at the <code><a href={aboutUrl}>About</a> section</code></li>
				<li>sources for ECMAScript information, take a look at the <code><a href={refUrl} target="_blank">References</a> readme</code></li>
			</ul>
			<p>Enjoy!</p>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
